# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brushless-dc-motors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A **brushless DC electric motor** (**BLDC**), also known as an **electronically commutated motor**, is a synchronous motor using a direct current (DC) electric power supply.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It uses an electronic controller to switch DC currents to the motor windings, producing magnetic fields that effectively rotate in space and which the permanent magnet rotor follows.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The controller adjusts the phase and amplitude of the current pulses that control the speed and torque of the motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It is an improvement on the mechanical commutator (brushes) used in many conventional electric motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The construction of a brushless motor system is typically similar to a permanent magnet synchronous motor (PMSM), but can also be a switched reluctance motor, or an induction (asynchronous) motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They may also use neodymium magnets and be outrunners (the stator is surrounded by the rotor), inrunners (the rotor is surrounded by the stator), or axial (the rotor and stator are flat and parallel).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The advantages of a brushless motor over brushed motors are high power-to-weight ratio, high speed, nearly instantaneous control of speed (rpm) and torque, high efficiency, and low maintenance.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors find applications in such places as computer peripherals (disk drives, printers), hand-held power tools, and vehicles ranging from model aircraft to automobiles.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In modern washing machines, brushless DC motors have allowed replacement of rubber belts and gearboxes by a direct-drive design.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors were invented in the 20th century and are still common.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless DC motors were made possible by the development of solid-state electronics in the 1960s.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] An electric motor develops torque by keeping the magnetic fields of the rotor (the rotating part of the machine) and the stator (the fixed part of the machine) misaligned.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] One or both sets of magnets are electromagnets, made of a coil of wire wound around an iron core.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] DC running through the wire winding creates the magnetic field, providing the power that runs the motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The misalignment generates a torque that tries to realign the fields.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] As the rotor moves and the fields come into alignment, it is necessary to move either the rotor's or stator's field to maintain the misalignment and continue to generate torque and movement.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The device that moves the fields based on the position of the rotor is called a commutator.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In brushed motors, this is done with a rotary switch on the motor's shaft called a commutator.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] It consists of a rotating cylinder or disc divided into multiple metal contact segments on the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The segments are connected to conductor windings on the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Two or more stationary contacts called *brushes*, made of a soft conductor such as graphite, press against the commutator, making sliding electrical contact with successive segments as the rotor turns.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The brushes selectively provide electric current to the windings.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] As the rotor rotates, the commutator selects different windings and the directional current is applied to a given winding such that the rotor's magnetic field remains misaligned with the stator and creates a torque in one direction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The brush commutator has disadvantages that have led to a decline in the use of brushed motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] During the last hundred years, high-power DC brushed motors, once the mainstay of industry, were replaced by alternating current (AC) synchronous motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Today, brushed motors are used only in low-power applications or where only DC is available, but the above drawbacks limit their use even in these applications.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In brushless DC motors, an electronic controller replaces the brush commutator contacts.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The elimination of the sliding contact allows brushless motors to have less friction and longer life; their working life is limited only by the lifetime of their bearings.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushed DC motors develop a maximum torque when stationary, linearly decreasing as velocity increases.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Some limitations of brushed motors can be overcome by brushless motors; they include higher efficiency and lower susceptibility to mechanical wear.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These benefits come at the cost of potentially less rugged, more complex, and more expensive control electronics.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A typical brushless motor has permanent magnets that rotate around a fixed armature, eliminating problems associated with connecting current to the moving armature.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] An electronic controller replaces the commutator assembly of the brushed DC motor, which continually switches the phase to the windings to keep the motor turning.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The controller performs similar timed power distribution by using a solid-state circuit rather than the commutator system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] With no windings on the rotor, they are not subjected to centrifugal forces, and because the windings are supported by the housing, they can be cooled by conduction, requiring no airflow inside the motor for cooling.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This, in turn, means that the motor's internals can be entirely enclosed and protected from dirt or other foreign matter.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motor commutation can be implemented in software using a microcontroller, or may alternatively be implemented using analog or digital circuits.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Commutation with electronics instead of brushes allows for greater flexibility and capabilities not available with brushed DC motors, including speed limiting, microstepping operation for slow and fine motion control, and holding torque when stationary.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Controller software can be customized to the specific motor being used in the application, resulting in greater commutation efficiency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The maximum power that can be applied to a brushless motor is limited almost exclusively by heat; too much heat weakens the magnets and damages the windings' insulation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] When converting electricity into mechanical power, brushless motors are more efficient than brushed motors primarily due to the absence of brushes, which reduces mechanical energy loss due to friction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The enhanced efficiency is greatest in the no-load and low-load regions of the motor's performance curve.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Environments and requirements in which manufacturers use brushless-type DC motors include maintenance-free operation, high speeds, and operation where sparking is hazardous (i.e., explosive environments) or could affect electronically sensitive equipment.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The construction of a brushless motor resembles a stepper motor, but the motors have important differences in implementation and operation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] While stepper motors are frequently stopped with the rotor in a defined angular position, a brushless motor is usually intended to produce continuous rotation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Both motor types may have a rotor position sensor for internal feedback.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Both a stepper motor and a well-designed brushless motor can hold finite torque at zero RPM.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Because the controller implements the traditional brushes' functionality, it needs to know the rotor's orientation relative to the stator coils.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is automatic in a brushed motor due to the fixed geometry of the rotor shaft and brushes.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Some designs use Hall effect sensors or a rotary encoder to directly measure the rotor's position.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Others measure the back-EMF in the undriven coils to infer the rotor position, eliminating the need for separate Hall effect sensors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These are therefore often called *sensorless* controllers.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Controllers that sense rotor position based on back-EMF have extra challenges in initiating motion because no back-EMF is produced when the rotor is stationary.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is usually accomplished by beginning rotation from an arbitrary phase, and then skipping to the correct phase if it is found to be wrong.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This can cause the motor to run backwards briefly, adding even more complexity to the startup sequence.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Other sensorless controllers are capable of measuring winding saturation caused by the position of the magnets to infer the rotor position.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A typical controller contains three polarity-reversible outputs controlled by a logic circuit.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Simple controllers employ comparators working from the orientation sensors to determine when the output phase should be advanced.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] More advanced controllers employ a microcontroller to manage acceleration, control motor speed and fine-tune efficiency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Two key performance parameters of brushless DC motors are the motor constants $K_{T}$ (torque constant) and $K_{e}$ (back-EMF constant, also known as speed constant $K_{V}={1 \over K_{e}}$ ).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors can be constructed in several different physical configurations.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the conventional inrunner configuration, the permanent magnets are part of the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Three stator windings surround the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the external-rotor outrunner configuration, the radial relationship between the coils and magnets is reversed; the stator coils form the center (core) of the motor, while the permanent magnets spin within an overhanging rotor that surrounds the core.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Outrunners typically have more poles and have a higher torque at low RPM.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the flat axial flux type, used where there are space or shape constraints, stator and rotor plates are mounted face to face.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In all brushless motors, the coils are stationary.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] This is for 3 phase AC motors not DC brushless motors: There are two common electrical winding configurations: the delta configuration connects three windings to each other in a triangle-like circuit, and power is applied at each of the connections.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The wye (*Y*-shaped) configuration, sometimes called a star winding, connects all of the windings to a central point, and power is applied to the remaining end of each winding.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A motor with windings in delta configuration gives low torque at low speed but can give a higher top speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Wye configuration gives high torque at low speed but not as high top speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The wye winding is normally more efficient.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Delta-connected windings can allow high-frequency parasitic electrical currents to circulate entirely within the motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] A Wye-connected winding does not contain a closed loop in which parasitic currents can flow, preventing such losses.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Aside from the higher impedance of the wye configuration, from a controller standpoint, the two winding configurations can be treated exactly the same.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors fulfill many functions originally performed by brushed DC motors, but cost and control complexity prevent brushless motors from replacing brushed motors completely in the lowest-cost areas.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Nevertheless, brushless motors have come to dominate many applications, particularly devices such as computer hard drives and CD/DVD players.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Small cooling fans in electronic equipment are powered exclusively by brushless motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They can be found in cordless power tools, where the increased efficiency of the motor leads to longer periods of use before the battery needs to be charged.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Low speed, low power brushless motors are used in direct-drive turntables for gramophone records.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors can also be found in marine applications, such as underwater thrusters.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Drones also utilize brushless motors to elevate their performance.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are found in electric vehicles, hybrid vehicles, personal transporters, and electric aircraft.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Most electric bicycles use brushless motors that are sometimes built into the wheel hub itself, with the stator fixed solidly to the axle and the magnets attached to and rotating with the wheel.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The same principle is applied in self-balancing scooter wheels.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Most electrically powered radio-controlled models use brushless motors because of their high efficiency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are found in many modern cordless tools, including some string trimmers, leaf blowers, saws (circular and reciprocating), and drills/drivers.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The weight and efficiency advantages of brushless over brushed motors are more important to handheld, battery-powered tools than to large, stationary tools plugged into an AC outlet.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] There is a trend in the heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) and refrigeration industries to use brushless motors instead of various types of AC motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The most significant reason to switch to a brushless motor is a reduction in power required to operate them versus a typical AC motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In addition to the brushless motor's higher efficiency, HVAC systems, especially those featuring variable-speed or load modulation, use brushless motors to give the built-in microprocessor continuous control over cooling and airflow.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The application of brushless DC motors within industrial engineering primarily focuses on manufacturing engineering or industrial automation design.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are ideally suited for manufacturing applications because of their high power density, good speed-torque characteristics, high efficiency, wide speed ranges and low maintenance.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The most common uses of brushless DC motors in industrial engineering are motion control, linear actuators, servomotors, actuators for industrial robots, extruder drive motors and feed drives for CNC machine tools.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are commonly used as pump, fan and spindle drives in adjustable or variable speed applications as they are capable of developing high torque with good speed response.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In addition, they can be easily automated for remote control.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Due to their construction, they have good thermal characteristics and high energy efficiency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] To obtain a variable speed response, brushless motors operate in an electromechanical system that includes an electronic motor controller and a rotor position feedback sensor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless DC motors are widely used as servomotors for machine tool servo drives.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Servomotors are used for mechanical displacement, positioning or precision motion control.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] DC stepper motors can also be used as servomotors; however, since they are operated with open loop control, they typically exhibit torque pulsations.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are used in industrial positioning and actuation applications.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] For assembly robots, Brushless technology may be used to build linear motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The advantage of linear motors is that they can produce linear motion without the need of a transmission system, such as ballscrews, leadscrew, rack-and-pinion, cam, gears or belts, that would be necessary for rotary motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Transmission systems are known to introduce less responsiveness and reduced accuracy.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Direct drive, brushless DC linear motors consist of a slotted stator with magnetic teeth and a moving actuator, which has permanent magnets and coil windings.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] To obtain linear motion, a motor controller excites the coil windings in the actuator causing an interaction of the magnetic fields resulting in linear motion.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Tubular linear motors are another form of linear motor design operated in a similar way.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors have become a popular motor choice for model aircraft, including helicopters and drones.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Their favorable power-to-weight ratios and wide range of available sizes have revolutionized the market for electric-powered model flight, displacing virtually all brushed electric motors, except for low powered inexpensive often toy grade aircraft.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They have also encouraged growth of simple, lightweight electric model aircraft, rather than the previous internal combustion engines powering larger and heavier models.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The increased power-to-weight ratio of modern batteries and brushless motors allows models to ascend vertically rather than climb gradually.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] The low noise and lack of mass compared to small glow fuel internal combustion engines is another reason for their popularity.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Their popularity has also risen in the radio-controlled car area.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors have been legal in North American RC car racing in accordance with Radio Operated Auto Racing (ROAR) since 2006.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] These motors provide a great amount of power to RC racers and, if paired with appropriate gearing and high-discharge lithium polymer (Li-Po) or lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO4) batteries, these cars can achieve speeds over 160 kilometres per hour (99 mph).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are capable of producing more torque and have a faster peak rotational speed compared to nitro- or gasoline-powered engines.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Nitro engines peak at around 46,800 r/min and 2.2 kilowatts (3.0 hp), while a smaller brushless motor can reach 50,000 r/min and 3.7 kilowatts (5.0 hp).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Larger brushless RC motors can reach upwards of 10 kilowatts (13 hp) and 28,000 r/min to power one-fifth-scale models.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are widely used as an alternative to brushed motors in the sport of combat robotics.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] They are used in every weight class from 75 grams all the way up to 250 pounds.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] When used for locomotion, brushless motors are often paired with a planetary gearbox in order to decrease the output speed to make the robot more controllable.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Other methods, such as friction drive, achieve the same result using slightly different means.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] Brushless motors are also often used to power kinetic weapons (such as a spinning blade).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/brushless-dc-electric-motor] In the lower weight classes, weapons are often mounted directly to the motor, while in heavier robots, timing belts, v-belts, and chains are used to transmit power from the motor to the spinning mass.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] FOC is used to control AC synchronous and induction motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] It was originally developed for high-performance motor applications that are required to operate smoothly over the full speed range, generate full torque at zero speed, and have high dynamic performance including fast acceleration and deceleration.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] However, it is becoming increasingly attractive for lower performance applications as well due to FOC's motor size, cost and power consumption reduction superiority.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] It is expected that with increasing computational power of the microprocessors it will eventually nearly universally displace single-variable scalar control (volts-per-Hertz, V/f control).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Blaschke pioneered vector control of AC motors starting in 1968 and in the early 1970s.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Hasse in terms of proposing indirect vector control, Blaschke in terms of proposing direct vector control.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Technical University Braunschweig's Werner Leonhard further developed FOC techniques and was instrumental in opening up opportunities for AC drives to be a competitive alternative to DC drives.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Yet it was not until after the commercialization of microprocessors, that is in the early 1980s, that general purpose AC drives became available.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Barriers to use FOC for AC drive applications included higher cost and complexity and lower maintainability compared to DC drives, FOC having until then required many electronic components in terms of sensors, amplifiers and so on.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] The Park transformation has long been widely used in the analysis and study of synchronous and induction machines.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] The transformation is by far the single most important concept needed for an understanding of how FOC works, the concept having been first conceptualized in a 1929 paper authored by Robert H.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Park's paper was ranked second most important in terms of impact from among all power engineering related papers ever published in the twentieth century.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] The novelty of Park's work involves his ability to transform any related machine's linear differential equation set from one with time varying coefficients to another with time *invariant* coefficients resulting in a linear time-invariant system or LTI system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] While the analysis of AC drive controls can be technically quite involved ("See also" section), such analysis invariably starts with modeling of the drive-motor circuit involved along the lines of accompanying signal flow graph and equations.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] In vector control, an AC induction or synchronous motor is controlled under all operating conditions like a separately excited DC motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Such complex stator current space vector can be defined in a (d,q) coordinate system with orthogonal components along d (direct) and q (quadrature) axes such that field flux linkage component of current is aligned along the d axis and torque component of current is aligned along the q axis.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] The induction motor's (d,q) coordinate system can be superimposed to the motor's instantaneous (a,b,c) three-phase sinusoidal system as shown in accompanying image (phases b & c not shown for clarity).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Components of the (d,q) system current vector allow conventional control such as proportional and integral, or PI, control, as with a DC motor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] The idea of using the park transform is to convert the system of three phase currents and voltages into a two coordinate linear time-invariant system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] By making the system LTI is what enables the use of simple and easy to implement PI controllers, and also simplifies the control of flux and torque producing currents.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] However, it is not uncommon for sources to use combined transform three-to-two, (a,b,c)-to-(d,q) and inverse projections.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Decoupled torque and field currents can thus be derived from raw stator current inputs for control algorithm development.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Inverters can be implemented as either open-loop sensorless or closed-loop FOC, the key limitation of open-loop operation being minimum speed possible at 100% torque, namely, about 0.8 Hz compared to standstill for closed-loop operation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] There are two vector control methods, direct or feedback vector control (DFOC) and indirect or feedforward vector control (IFOC), IFOC being more commonly used because in closed-loop mode such drives more easily operate throughout the speed range from zero speed to high-speed field-weakening.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] In DFOC, flux magnitude and angle feedback signals are directly calculated using so-called voltage or current models.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] In IFOC, flux space angle feedforward and flux magnitude signals first measure stator currents and rotor speed for then deriving flux space angle proper by summing the rotor angle corresponding to the rotor speed and the calculated reference value of slip angle corresponding to the slip frequency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Sensorless control (see the Sensorless FOC block diagram) of AC drives is attractive for cost and reliability considerations.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Sensorless control requires derivation of rotor speed information from measured stator voltage and currents in combination with open-loop estimators or closed-loop observers.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Current is converted to ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Transformed to a coordinate system rotating in rotor reference frame, rotor position is derived by integrating the speed by means of speed measurement sensor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Rotor flux linkage vector is estimated by multiplying the stator current vector with magnetizing inductance Lm and low-pass filtering the result with the rotor no-load time constant Lr/Rr, namely, the rotor inductance to rotor resistance ratio.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Current vector is converted to (d,q) coordinate system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] 5. d-axis component of the stator current vector is used to control the rotor flux linkage and the imaginary q-axis component is used to control the motor torque.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] While PI controllers can be used to control these currents, bang-bang type current control provides better dynamic performance.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] PI controllers provide (d,q) coordinate voltage components.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] A decoupling term is sometimes added to the controller output to improve control performance to mitigate cross coupling or big and rapid changes in speed, current and flux linkage.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] PI-controller also sometimes need low-pass filtering at the input or output to prevent the current ripple due to transistor switching from being amplified excessively and destabilizing the control.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] However, such filtering also limits the dynamic control system performance.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] High switching frequency (typically more than 10 kHz) is typically required to minimize filtering requirements for high-performance drives such as servo drives.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Voltage components are transformed from (d,q) coordinate system to ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Voltage components are transformed from ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system to (a,b,c) coordinate system or fed in Pulse-Width Modulation (PWM) modulator, or both, for signaling to the power inverter section.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Although the vector control algorithm is more complicated than the Direct Torque Control (DTC), the algorithm need not be calculated as frequently as the DTC algorithm.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Also the current sensors need not be the best in the market.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/field-oriented-control] Thus the cost of the processor and other control hardware is lower making it suitable for applications where the ultimate performance of DTC is not required.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A **synchronous electric motor** is an AC electric motor in which, at steady state, the rotation of the shaft is synchronized with the frequency of the supply current.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors use permanent magnets or electromagnets for rotors, and electromagnets for stators.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The stator creates a magnetic field that rotates in time with the oscillations of the current.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotor turns in step with the stator field at the same rate and as a result, provides a second synchronized rotating magnet field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous and induction motors are the most widely used AC motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors rotate at a rate locked to the line frequency since they do not rely on induction to produce the rotor's magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Induction motors require *slip*: the rotor must rotate at a frequency slightly slower than the AC alternations in order to induce current in the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors are available in self-excited, fractional to industrial sizes.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In the fractional power range, most synchronous motors are used to provide precise constant speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] These machines are commonly used in analog electric clocks, timers and related devices.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Doubly fed synchronous motors use independently-excited multiphase AC electromagnets for both rotor and stator.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In typical industrial sizes, the synchronous motor provides an efficient means of converting AC energy to work (electrical efficiency above 95% is normal for larger sizes) and it can operate at leading or unity power factor and thereby provide power-factor correction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors fall under the category of *synchronous machines* that also includes synchronous generators.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Generator action occurs if the field poles are "driven ahead of the resultant air-gap flux by the forward motion of the prime mover".
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Motor action occurs if the field poles are "dragged behind the resultant air-gap flux by the retarding torque of a shaft load".
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The two major types of synchronous motors are distinguished by how the rotor is magnetized: non-excited and direct-current excited.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In non-excited motors, the external stator field magnetizes the rotor, inducing the magnetic poles needed to turn the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotor rotates in step with the stator's rotating magnetic field, so it has an almost-constant magnetic field through it.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotor is made of a high-retentivity steel such as cobalt steel.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A permanent-magnet synchronous motor (PMSM) uses permanent magnets embedded in the rotor to create a constant magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The stator carries windings connected to an AC electricity supply to produce a rotating magnetic field (as in an asynchronous motor).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] At synchronous speed the rotor poles lock to the rotating magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] PMSMs are similar to brushless DC motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Neodymium magnets are the most common, although rapid fluctuation of neodymium magnet prices triggered research in ferrite magnets.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Due to inherent characteristics of ferrite magnets, the magnetic circuit of these machines needs to be able to concentrate the magnetic flux, typically leading to the use of spoke type rotors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Machines that use ferrite magnets have lower power density and torque density when compared with neodymium machines.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] PMSMs have been used as gearless elevator motors since 2000.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Most PMSMs require a variable-frequency drive to start them.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] However, some incorporate a squirrel cage in the rotor for starting—these are known as line-start or self-starting.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] These are typically used as higher-efficiency replacements for induction motors (owing to the lack of slip), but must ensure that synchronous speed is reached and that the system can withstand torque ripple during starting.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] PMSMs are typically controlled using direct torque control and field oriented control.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Reluctance motors have a solid steel cast rotor with projecting (salient) toothed poles.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Typically there are fewer rotor than stator poles to minimize torque ripple and to prevent the poles from all aligning simultaneously—a position that cannot generate torque.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The size of the air gap in the magnetic circuit and thus the reluctance is minimum when the poles align with the stator's (rotating) magnetic field, and increases with the angle between them.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This creates torque that pulls the rotor into alignment with the nearest pole of the stator field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] At synchronous speed the rotor is thus "locked" to the rotating stator field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This cannot start the motor, so the rotor poles usually have squirrel-cage windings embedded in them, to provide torque below synchronous speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The machine thus starts as an induction motor until it approaches synchronous speed, when the rotor "pulls in" and locks to the stator field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Reluctance motor designs have ratings that range from fractional horsepower (a few watts) to about 22 kW.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Small reluctance motors have low torque, and are generally used for instrumentation applications.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Moderate torque, multi-horsepower motors use squirrel cage construction with toothed rotors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] When used with an adjustable frequency power supply, all motors in a drive system can operate at exactly the same speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The power supply frequency determines motor operating speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Hysteresis motors have a solid, smooth, cylindrical rotor, cast of a high coercivity magnetically "hard" cobalt steel.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This material has a wide hysteresis loop (high coercivity), meaning once it is magnetized in a given direction, it requires a high magnetic field to reverse the magnetization.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotating stator field causes each small volume of the rotor to experience a reversing magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Because of hysteresis the phase of the magnetization lags behind the phase of the applied field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Thus the axis of the magnetic field induced in the rotor lags behind the axis of the stator field by a constant angle δ, producing torque as the rotor tries to "catch up" with the stator field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] As long as the rotor is below synchronous speed, each particle of the rotor experiences a reversing magnetic field at the "slip" frequency that drives it around its hysteresis loop, causing the rotor field to lag and create torque.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotor has a 2-pole low reluctance bar structure.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] As the rotor approaches synchronous speed and slip goes to zero, this magnetizes and aligns with the stator field, causing the rotor to "lock" to the rotating stator field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A major advantage of the hysteresis motor is that since the lag angle δ is independent of speed, it develops constant torque from startup to synchronous speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Therefore, it is self-starting and doesn't need an induction winding to start it, although many designs embed a squirrel-cage conductive winding structure in the rotor to provide extra torque at start-up.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Hysteresis motors are manufactured in sub-fractional horsepower ratings, primarily as servomotors and timing motors.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] More expensive than the reluctance type, hysteresis motors are used where precise constant speed is required.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Usually made in larger sizes (larger than about 1 horsepower or 1 kilowatt) these motors require direct current (DC) to excite (magnetize) the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This is most straightforwardly supplied through slip rings.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A brushless AC induction and rectifier arrangement can also be used.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A permanent magnet synchronous motor and reluctance motor requires a control system for operating (VFD or servo drive).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] There is a large number of control methods for synchronous machines, selected depending on the construction of the electric motor and the scope.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The PMSMs can also operate on open-loop control, which is sometimes used for start-up thus enabling the position sensing operation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A single-phase, 4-pole (2-pole-pair) synchronous motor is operating at an AC supply frequency of 50 Hz.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A three-phase, 12-pole (6-pole-pair) synchronous motor is operating at an AC supply frequency of 60 Hz.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The number of magnetic poles, p , is equal to the number of coil groups per phase.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] To determine the number of coil groups per phase in a 3-phase motor, count the number of coils, divide by the number of phases, which is 3.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The coils may span several slots in the stator core, making it tedious to count them.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] For a 3-phase motor, if you count a total of 12 coil groups, it has 4 magnetic poles.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] For a 12-pole 3-phase machine, there will be 36 coils.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The number of magnetic poles in the rotor is equal to the number of magnetic poles in the stator.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The principal components of electric motors are the stator and the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Synchronous motor and induction motor stators are similar in construction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The construction of synchronous motor is similar to that of an alternator (also called synchronous generator).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The stator frame contains wrapper plate (except for wound-rotor synchronous doubly fed electric machines).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Circumferential ribs and keybars are attached to the wrapper plate.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] To carry the weight of the machine, frame mounts and footings are required.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The synchronous stator winding consists of a 3 phase winding.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] It is provided with a 3 phase supply, and the rotor is provided with a DC supply.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] DC excited motors require brushes and slip rings to connect to the excitation supply.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The field winding can be excited by a brushless exciter.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Cylindrical, round rotors, (also known as non-salient pole rotor) are used for up to six poles.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In some machines or when a large number of poles are needed, a salient pole rotor is used.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Most synchronous motor construction uses a stationary armature and rotating field winding.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This type of construction has an advantage over DC motor type where the armature used is of rotating type.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Electric motors generate power due to the interaction of the magnetic fields of the stator and the rotor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In synchronous motors, the stator carries 3 phase currents and produces 3 phase rotating magnetic flux (and therefore a rotating magnetic field).
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The rotor eventually locks in with the rotating magnetic field and rotates along with it.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Once the rotor field locks in with the rotating magnetic field, the motor is said to be synched.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] A single-phase (or two-phase derived from single phase) stator is possible, but in this case the direction of rotation is not defined and the machine may start in either direction unless prevented from doing so by startup arrangements.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Once the motor is in operation, the speed of the motor is dependent only on the supply frequency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] When the motor load is increased beyond the breakdown load, the motor falls out of synchronization and the rotor no longer follows the rotating magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Since the motor cannot produce torque if it falls out of synchronization, practical synchronous motors have a partial or complete squirrel-cage damper called an *amortisseur* winding to stabilize operation and facilitate starting.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Above a certain size, synchronous motors cannot self-start.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This property is due to rotor inertia; it cannot instantly follow the rotation of the stator's magnetic field.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Since a synchronous motor produces no inherent average torque at standstill, it cannot accelerate to synchronous speed without a supplemental mechanism.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Large motors operating on commercial power include a squirrel-cage induction winding that provides sufficient torque for acceleration and also serves to damp motor speed oscillations.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Once the rotor nears the synchronous speed, the field winding becomes excited and the motor pulls into synchronization.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Very large motor systems may include a "pony" motor that accelerates the unloaded synchronous machine before load is applied.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Electronically controlled motors can be accelerated from zero speed by changing the frequency of the stator current.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Small synchronous motors are commonly used in line-powered electric mechanical clocks or timers that use the power line frequency to run the gear mechanism at the correct speed.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Such small synchronous motors are able to start without assistance if the moment of inertia of the rotor and its mechanical load are sufficiently small.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The motor accelerates from slip speed to synchronous speed during an accelerating half cycle of the reluctance torque.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Single-phase synchronous motors such as in electric wall clocks can freely rotate in either direction, unlike a shaded-pole type.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Costs are an important parameter for starters.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Rotor excitation is a possible way to resolve the issue.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In addition, starting methods for large synchronous machines include repetitive polarity inversion of the rotor poles during startup.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] By varying the excitation of a synchronous motor, it can be made to operate at lagging, leading and unity power factor.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Excitation at which the power factor is unity is termed *normal excitation voltage*.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The magnitude of current at this excitation is minimum.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Excitation voltage more than normal excitation is called over excitation voltage, excitation voltage less than normal excitation is called under excitation.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] When the motor is over excited, the back emf will be greater than the motor terminal voltage.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This causes a demagnetizing effect due to armature reaction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The V curve of a synchronous machine shows armature current as a function of field current.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] With increasing field current armature current at first decreases, then reaches a minimum, then increases.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The minimum point is also the point at which power factor is unity.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] This ability to selectively control power factor can be exploited for power factor correction of the power system to which the motor is connected.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Since most power systems of any significant size have a net lagging power factor, the presence of overexcited synchronous motors moves the system's net power factor closer to unity, improving efficiency.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] Such power-factor correction is usually a side effect of motors already present in the system to provide mechanical work, although motors can be run without mechanical load simply to provide power-factor correction.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] In large industrial plants such as factories the interaction between synchronous motors and other, lagging, loads may be an explicit consideration in the plant's electrical design.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] When load is applied, torque angle $\delta$ increases.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] When $\delta$ = 90° the torque will be maximum.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] If load is applied further then the motor will lose its synchronism, since motor torque will be less than load torque.
[src:brushless-dc-motors/permanent-magnet-synchronous-motor] The maximum load torque that can be applied to a motor without losing its synchronism is called steady state stability limit of a synchronous motor.
